DIV2.P:
P. 47. When in Bedlam, Lee was visited by Sir Roger L'Estrange; who said, “I believe you don't recollect me, Mr. Lee.” He replied, "Yes, I do very well—
“Faces may alter, names can't change;
endq;I'm strange Lee alter'd, you are still L'Estrange. See more of Lee, Biog. Brit. VI.2913.

P. 161. Dr. Evans 'on Bleheim' reminds me of Lord Chesterfield telling Geo. Wade, after Lord Burlington had built him a house in Burlington Gardens, with a most elegant front, but very inconvenient within, that he did not make the proper use of it. 'How so, my Lord? I live in it.'— "True," says the Earl;
“but, if I were you, I would take a house over against it, to admire that beautiful front.”
D.
